{{Infobox NFL season | logo = | team = Cincinnati Bengals | year = 2009 | record = 10â6<!--Do not add zero ties--> | division_place = 1st [[AFC North]] | coach = [[Marvin Lewis]] | stadium = [[Paul Brown Stadium]] | playoffs = Lost [[2009â10 NFL playoffs|Wild Card Playoffs]] ([[New York Jets|Jets]]) 24â14 | pro bowlers = WR [[Chad Ochocinco]] | AP All-pros = [[Leon Hall]] ''(2nd team)'' | uniform = File:AFCN-Uniform-CIN.PNG }}
The '''[[2009 NFL season|2009]] [[Cincinnati Bengals]] season''' was the 40th season for the team in the [[National Football League]] and their 42nd overall. They finished the season at 10â6â0, and sweeping the entire AFC North division, they improved on their 2008 record of 4â11â1, winning the AFC North Division and making the playoffs for the first time since [[2005 Cincinnati Bengals season|2005]]. Their season ended with a 24â14 loss against the [[New York Jets]] in the AFC Wild Card Playoff Round.
The head coach was [[Marvin Lewis]], who has coached the team since 2003. He was chosen by the [[Associated Press]] as its [[National Football League Coach of the Year Award|NFL Coach of the Year]] following the season. Lewis was recognized for turning around the Bengals in the face of serious off-the-field adversity. First, three players were personally affected by the [[2009 Samoa earthquake|tsunami]] that hit [[American Samoa]] in late September. Shortly after this disaster, Vikki Zimmer, the wife of defensive coordinator [[Mike Zimmer]], unexpectedly died. Finally, wide receiver [[Chris Henry (wide receiver)|Chris Henry]], who suffered a season-ending injury in Week 9, died in December from injuries suffered when he fell from the back of a pickup truck during a domestic dispute.<ref name="Lewis COY">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4831442 |title=Lewis named coach of year |agency=Associated Press |publisher=''ESPN.com'' |date=2010-01-16 |accessdate=2010-01-16}}</ref>
